				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: WARNING!  New mob in FEAR.<a name="21759"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Feb 17 04 3:25 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Not sure if this has been mentioned, but--
<br />

<br />
The other night, I was solo'ing in Fear trying to get the Amy Whip for my Epic. I was on my Wizard (he's bound there) so was only killing one at a time, porting out to Nexus, then gating back inside. I had made a nice dent in the North Western corner of the zone (the area west of the ring of fire) so I was able to pretty much get singles into that area. 
<br />

<br />
From what I can tell, assuming it happens the same every time, the Ireblind Imp will spawn *immediately* after the death of a *random* scareling. I'm guessing it's random, much like named pops off luggalds and trolls in Crypt of Nadox. Having never even heard of this guy, though, when a giant red imp popped immediately after killing a scareling, needless to say, I was rather unnerved.
<br />

<br />
I had a few seconds (after recovering from shock) to run off and try to land a snare. No good-- Immune to changes in run speed. About that time, I was stunned and awaited my death that would probably take a raid force to recover from. For some reason (I assumed I was mezzed) he wouldn't attack, so after the stun/mez fell, I managed to gate out.
<br />

<br />
Well, after taking a few deep breaths, I managed to put two and two together, and figured it was a new epic mob. Never one to be swayed by such things as certain death and higher reason, I gated back to Fear and tried my luck.
<br />

<br />
A few on Alla's mentioned it, but I'll reiterate it -- The first spell I tried was a stun spell -- It didn't resist the spell (took damage (which, for about 1k damage, only dropped it to 99%)) however, it came immediately after me. Stuns didn't seem to affect it, but there is no message at the time to confirm it.
<br />

<br />
Well, I ran around a bit -- Another note, it doesn't run as fast as regular scarelings. I let it get close and tried to channel off a nuke, but was stunned again. However, unlike the first time I encountered it, I was right next to it when I was stunned. So as soon as the mez broke, it began hitting me again-- so I ran off a ways-- and this time when mez broke, I was able to port out again.
<br />

<br />
Now, while I was able to survive a couple encounters with the guy, that was because I was alone, and there were no other Fear mobs around. I can see how this could cause massive trouble to a raid force during break in, or in any instance where there are other mobs to pounce on you as soon as the mez breaks.
<br />

<br />
Heh, sorry, I've taken the Bard thing a bit to heart. Allow me to summarize, and add a few notes about this guy:
<br />

<br />
1) Ireblind Imp will randomly pop immediately after a scareling is killed. It will pop directly over the corpse.
<br />
2) Ireblind Imp is blue to level 65. It cannot be snared or rooted. It is not affected by stuns, whether intentional or not. It does see through invisible. However, it has a very small aggro range, nothing like the actual scarelings, or other Fear mobs. Also, I do not know if it summons, I didn't get it low enough.
<br />
3) The Imp looks just like a regular scareling, but is a lot larger. It's hard to miss.
<br />
4) The Imp has a rather large AE, unresistable (I hear) Mez/Stun that lasts for several seconds (sorry, not certain on details) -- However, the mez/stun also acts as a mem blur on itself. That means, if you are mezzed outside of its aggro range, it will forget about you and wander back.
<br />
5) Wander back where, you ask? The Imp will always return to where it was spawned-- the point where you killed the scareling from which it popped. I can't guarantee this is the case all the time, but from my experience, it certainly seems to hold true. People were talking about how the Imp was camping their corpses-- I believe this was because they killed a scareling in camp, the Imp popped, and merely returned to spawn spot each time.
<br />
6) Only from what I read, at various stages in its life, (80% health, 60% health) it will spawn smaller imps, around six, that will also attack, and also cannot be snared/rooted.
<br />
7) Again, from my own experience, I do not believe it despawns, well, ever (besides obvious server resets). I know at the very least it stayed in Fear for several hours after it was spawned-- however, it was easy to work around (for me, merely because it was placed at the very most northern part of the zone).
<br />

<br />
Now, just a quick few suggestions I may make-- If you're breaking Fear with a raid, save the scarelings for last (which likely should be the case anyway, to cause the least damage from teleports). I can't give much advice on actually killing the guy, but if you need to recover from a wipe, and Fear is relatively clear, you can probably grab your corpses and run away, wait until he mezzes you, then wanders back, and then rez yourself. Can likely repeat this as many times as you need to, as long as no other mobs come to disturb you.
<br />

<br />
Well, sorry about the long-wind-ed-ness, but figured I'd give any information that I could offer. That being said, however, the Amy Whip is a pain. *sighs* -- Heh, good luck.
<br />

<br />
Kinrian
<br />
52 Bard
<br />
Morrel-Thule</span></td>
